## Context: read first

Before substantive work, read:

- `.github/context/*.md` (for example `ARCHITECTURE.md`, `API_SURFACE.md`, `MODULE_MAP.md`, `CONVENTIONS.md`, `CHANGELOG_RECENT.md`)
- `docs/decisions/` (ADRs)
- `docs/plans/` (intended work)
- `docs/implementations/` (what was built)

If the repo has a `docs/README.md` or index, read it once for navigation.

## Tiered workflow (S / A / B / C)

Every change uses a branch, pull request, tests, lint, and security checks. The tier sets ceremony and review, not whether those steps run.

| Tier | Scope | Ceremony | Review |
|------|-------|----------|--------|
| **S** | Schema, security, infrastructure | Highest; human review | Human required |
| **A** | New features, integrations | High; human review | Human required |
| **B** | Enhancements to existing behavior | Medium | Auto-merge if green |
| **C** | Trivial (docs, typos, comments) | Low | Auto-merge if green |

Conventional commits: `feat|fix|docs|refactor|test|chore|ci|perf: description`

Full detail: `.github/instructions/workflow.md`

## Critical guardrails

**NEVER:** drop a database or apply destructive schema without explicit approval; delete infrastructure files (Makefile, CI, deploy scripts); push directly to `main`; skip tests; store secrets in code or commit credentials; leave TODO/FIXME/HACK in committed code; add ghost implementations; silence errors with bare `except:` or `except: pass`.

**ALWAYS:** run tests before and after changes; update `.github/context/` when architecture, APIs, or modules change; verify imports resolve; keep functions under 50 lines; prefer editing existing files over adding new ones; match the style of the surrounding code.

Full lists and verification: `.github/instructions/guardrails.md`
